We can graph $y=f(x)$ by looking at the piecewise definition of $f(x)$ in the given graph. First, $y=-2-x$ when $-3 \leq x \leq 0,$ so we draw a line segment with slope $-1$ passing through $(-3,-1)$ and $(0,-2).$ Next, $y=\sqrt{4-(x-2)^2}-2$ when $0 \leq x \leq 2,$ so we graph the top half of the circle centered at $(2,-2)$ with radius $2.$ Finally, $y=2(x-2)$ when $2 \leq x \leq 3,$ so we draw a line segment with slope $2$ passing through $(2,-2)$ and $(3,0).$

To graph $y=f(2x+1),$ we need to replace each instance of $x$ with $2x+1$ in the definition of $f(x).$ First, we plot $y=f(x)$ and $y=f(2x+1)$ on the same coordinate plane.

