To determine whether $f(x)$ is even, odd, or neither, we need to check whether it satisfies the conditions of these types of functions: 

- Even function: $f(x) = f(-x)$ for all $x$
- Odd function: $f(x) = -f(-x)$ for all $x$

Let's start with the even function condition. We want to check whether $f(x) = f(-x)$ for all $x$:

\begin{align*}
f(-x) &= (-1)^{\lfloor -x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( -x - \lfloor -x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} \\
&= (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor - 1} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( -x + \lfloor x \rfloor + \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} \\
&= \begin{cases} (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor - 1} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} & \text{if } x \text{ is not an integer} \\ (-1)^{-n-1} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}} = (-1)^{-n-1} \frac{1}{2} & \text{if } x = n \text{ for some integer } n \end{cases}
\end{align*}

Now we can compare $f(-x)$ to $f(x)$:

\begin{align*}
f(x) - f(-x) &= (-1)^{\lfloor x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} - (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor - 1} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} \\
&= \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if } x = n + \frac{1}{2} \text{ for some integer } n \\ 2(-1)^{\lfloor x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} & \text{if } x \text{ is not an integer} \\ \frac{1}{2}((-1)^{\lfloor x \rfloor} - (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor - 1}) & \text{if } x = n \text{ for some integer } n \end{cases}
\end{align*}

From this expression, we can see that $f(x) = f(-x)$ if and only if $x$ is an integer plus or minus $\frac{1}{2}$. In all other cases, $f(x) \neq f(-x)$. Therefore, $f(x)$ is not an even function.

Now let's move on to the odd function condition. We want to check whether $f(x) = -f(-x)$ for all $x$:

\begin{align*}
-f(-x) &= -(-1)^{\lfloor -x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( -x - \lfloor -x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} \\
&= (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} \\
&= \begin{cases} (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} & \text{if } x \text{ is not an integer} \\ (-1)^{-n} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4}} = (-1)^{-n} \frac{1}{2} & \text{if } x = n \text{ for some integer } n \end{cases}
\end{align*}

Now we can compare $f(-x)$ to $-f(x)$:

\begin{align*}
-f(x) - f(-x) &= -(-1)^{\lfloor x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} - (-1)^{-\lfloor x \rfloor} \sqrt{\frac{1}{4} - \left( x - \lfloor x \rfloor - \frac{1}{2} \right)^2} \\
&= 0
\end{align*}

This expression simplifies to 0 for all $x$, so we have $f(x) = -f(-x)$ for all $x$. Therefore, $f(x)$ is an odd function.

